id: How to Rebrand a Logo (Design Theory) [BjdWXqNIBq8]
title: How to Rebrand a Logo (Design Theory)
subtitle: similar but different was a term ilearned about in design school and it'sa theory that visual appeal is based onthe balance of something newbut not too new so if we look at theevolution of the classic chairyou'll see that over time popular chairswere adventurous but didn't go outsidethe boundaries of what was expected atthe timeif we compare the modern chair to theoldest one there's no way the modernversion would have survived back thensince it would be toounusual for the culture of that era thisis why we'll often seeunderappreciated art or products that wecall ahead of their timebecause back then people just didn't getit if we apply this to logo designsome of the strongest rebrands are theones that retain pieces of the previousidentitywhile the most controversial rebrandscompletely overhauled the identity andleave the previous logo behindthere are times when overhauls might benecessary but it's important to keepthis theory in mind when designing for aclientthat already has a culture built intotheir brand thanks for watching andfollow if you're interested in learningmore design school principles for free

subtitle: Creativity is an art.Art is neither learned nor taught.You oughtta absorb art within yourself.Language is an art.Now I'm speaking Urdu, without any thoughts,no problem at all.But if I'm to speak any other languages,it's way tough!I've not learned in any institute,even you haven't learned your mother language like this.We've seen other people speaking.Bring creativity to your own environment.Now it's not possible to just sit in art galleries.But you've got internet!Pick any image everyday,observe what designs are used there,what kind of colours and typographies used,for 10 mins just observe what has been done there.It'll gradually be part of your subconscious brain.And when you'll sit to design,you won't even imagine how smoothly you'll get creative ideas!But, not just one image,you'll have to do this assignment lifelong.Daily at night take an image,observe it,and trust me, it'll work.Will take time, but it surely will work!

subtitle: no idea about semantics or why it's soimportant well here's a powerful examplelinked to the British honor System andwhy King Charles wants to change it sosemantics is concerned with the meaningand impact of words and how particularwords connote particular things sotaking the British honor System as anexample titles like order of the BritishEmpire have sparked controversy becausethe word empire connotes Britain'sColonial past which many feel isoutdated and harmful so King Charles isreportedly considering removing Empirefrom these titles to move the shift awayfrom the colonial associations tosomething more positive like order ofBritish Excellence this example showsthat word choice isn't just aboutliteral meaning it can reflect valueshistory and the emotional impact whenyou analyze semantics in literature youare looking at how these words shapeyour understanding just like how thesetitles influence how people feel aboutthe British Monarchy understandingsemantics can elevate your grade becauseit demonstrates that you understand thedeeper impact of words so look at wordsbeyond their definitions and see howthey shape perspective

id: Denotational Semantics [NNQHuxQhlkY]
title: Denotational Semantics
subtitle: Denotational semantics.What does code really mean? Ever wonderwhat your code truly means? Not just howit runs, but its fundamentalmathematical definition. That's theworld of denotational semantics.Back in the day, programming languagemeanings were often vague, leading tobugs and confusion. But then brilliantminds like Christopher Stretchy and DanaScott asked what if we could map everypiece of code, a number, an operation, aloop directly to a precise mathematicalconcept. This gave us denotationalsemantics, assigning a clear, undeniablemathematical meaning to code. It bringsincredible precision, allowing us tomathematically prove programs arecorrect and design languages withabsolute clarity. It's the quietfoundational language ensuring ourdigital world makes sense.

subtitle: Friends, we know that broadly there arefour states of matter: solid,liquid, gas, and plasma. Here, wewant to study the mechanical properties of solid state materials. We knowthat a solid is one that has afixed size, fixed shape, andfixed volume. A solid is a compoundmade of an element. Supposewe have a box made of a fixed compound, i.e.,iron. That iron is made of fissile molecules,and thosemolecules are made upof atoms. Now, this was a very interesting question in 17th centurysolid state physics:how do solids remain in their fixed size and shape?Why don't they separate like liquids and gases?It was believed that there is anintermolecular force between the molecules of a solid,which is stronger than that of a liquid and a gas,and it keeps them closed.Remember, theforce between molecules is anintermolecular force, and the atomsfrom which molecules the molecules are made are called atoms.  They are made up of atoms and there is anintermolecular force between them.

subtitle: You've likely only seen plain tyres in Formula 1 racing,butthree types of tyres are primarily used in Formula 1 racing cars. Thefirst is a plain tyre,which lacks any grooves. These tyres aredesigned for dry conditions and can't run on water at all, butthey have excellent grip on a dry track. Thesecond is a grooved tyre, which isused for dam conditions and wetconditions. If you pour water on this tyre, thewater will pass through these grooves,maintaining the tyre's grip on the track. Next comes a deeper groovedtyre, with deeper grooves.These tyres are useful when there's a lot ofwater on the track. Thistype can literally cross 85 litres of water per second at aspeed of 300 km/h andmaintains good grip on the track.Like the video and subscribe to Life Stick.

subtitle: You know that ice freezes at 0°C, but there is atemperature lower than 0°C. Thecoldest temperature ever recorded on Earth is89.2°C, which wasrecorded in Antarctica in July 1983,but this cold is nothing. Ifwe talk about outer space, theaverage temperature of our space is 270°C,and this temperature is very close to absolute zero.273.5°C is considered absolute zero, and thistemperature is the lowest possibletemperature in the universe. This means that nothing colder than this exists.This is the ultimate limit. Atthis temperature, the movement of molecules becomesnegligible, and all chemicalreactions stop.Trillions of chemical reactions are going on in our body right now. Ifthis does not happen, our brain willnot be able to communicate with our body, due to whichwe will not even be able to breathe.

id: Binary Search Algorithm - Simply Explained [uTyxscVC_-U]
title: Binary Search Algorithm - Simply Explained
subtitle: Gautam is so important that we can see its implementation inalmost every computer science language. Let'ssay we are given the names of 100,000 people.One way is to giveus all the names in a list,and the other way is to giveus all the names written in a dictionary,starting with A, then B, then C. Inthis way, ifwe are told to find our name, it will be easier tofind it in which one.Obviously, it will be easier for us to find it in the dictionarybecause we can match the first letter of our name, whether itappears at the beginning or the end of the dictionary.This concept of binary search algorithm in coding works in such a waythat if we haveall the numbers written in ascending fashion from one to 10 andwe want to find the number eight, then tofind it, instead of looking at each number one by one, we willdivide our list into two partsand find the middle one.  Themiddle one is five. Now the number eight that we have tofind is greater than five, so we donot need to check it in the first list, we will directly pick up the second one andcheck in that. Now to check in the second list also,we will divide it into two piecesand take out our middle one andin the middle of these two pieces we will find ournumber eight. Now there isno need to find the left part, we need tofind the right part, so in this wayour magnetic reduces the coding.

So,brother, three willnot be the answer because we have to take variation, so thecombination here will be that and the answeris possible. For 3factorial, we will write three, so this iscancelled, this will become 3 * 3 = m, this will beforced up. So, if we solve this, theanswer comes out to be 84. So,we can make 84 such comedians. subtitle: As you can see, you need to pointthe nose towards the crosswind, andthen the difficulty will bebringing your nose back towards the runway. There aredifferent methods, such as a crablanding. This involves touching down withone landing gear, and once that wheel ison the ground, bringing the rest of the aircraft back.Each aircraft has its own method, andeach pilot may also have apreferred method. Generally speaking,landing gear isextremely robust and can withstand thecrosswind forces imposed by crab landing.Then, once the aircraftis on the ground, you bring it back into line with the runway. Becareful: if you bring the aircraft back intoline with the runway while in flight, the wind willpush you, and you could end up off-center, which might force you to makea recovery.

title: Role of Al-Farabi in the Development of Logic
subtitle: Al Farabi, often revered as the secondteacher after Aristotle, made monumentalcontributions to the field of logic inIslamic scholarship. During the 10thcentury, he built upon the works ofGreek philosophers, integratingAristotilian logic with Islamicprinciples, which played a crucial rolein shaping Islamic philosophy. Hiscomprehensive categorization of logicalfallacies and ideas about the functionsof language laid important foundationsfor future Islamic scholars andinfluenced Christian and Jewish thinkersduring the Middle Ages. Particularlynoteworthy is his book Kitab Al Borhanwhere he synthesized logic andepistemology emphasizing the importanceof demonstrative reasoning. Alfarabi'sadvances in logical thinking werepivotal in creating a philosophical andscientific environment that fosteredintellectual innovation.

subtitle: Equivalent Rational Number The basic property of a rational number isthat if itsnumerator and denominator aremultiplied or divided by the same number, then there isno change in its value, which means its value isequivalent. So, in this way,if we want to find the rational equivalent rational number of -2 up to 7, then ifwe multiply it by the same two on top, thenwe will multiply it by the same number below as well.Similarly,if we want to find the second equivalent, thenwe multiply it by three further, then we willmultiply it by the same seven below as well by three. In this way,if we want to find any equivalent rational number,we will keep moving up and down by that many digits in this way. Inthis way, -2 *2 = 4, 7 * 2 = 14, -2 * 3 = 6 and 7 * 3 = 21.What will be the equivalent rational number of 5 / -3, pleasetell us in the comments.

There aretwo methods to find out equivalent rational number and the method is this,you have a given rational number, you have to multiply itand if it is a small number thenyou multiply it by a common number i.e. 1/2 number andmake it equivalent,like in 2/3 wewill multiply it by 1/2, four upon six will come, if wemultiply it by 3 we will get 6/9, this ishow wemake it, the next method is if youhave a big number and you have to findout its equivalent thendivide it by a common number i.e. 1/2 number,like if we divide 24/30 by 1/2 thenit will become 12/15, if wedivide 12/15 by 3 then it will become 12  4/5So in this way wefind out the number according to two methods very easily.Description to study long video

subtitle: Implementing differential privacyinvolves several sophisticatedtechniques. One fundamental method isadding noise to data. This noise iscarefully calibrated to mask individualdata entries while allowing accuratestatistical queries. Differentiallyprivate algorithms are designed tooperate within a defined privacy budgetwhich quantifies the acceptable loss ofprivacy. Advanced cryptographic methodssuch as secure multi-party computationcan also be employed to enhance privacyand security in federated learning.These techniques ensure that whileindividual data points remain hidden,the overall model can still learneffectively from the data set.

title: This AI Secret Keeps Your Data Safe (Differentially Private Clipped-SGD) #Shorts
subtitle: Ever wonder how your phone's voiceassistant gets smarter without stealingyour secrets? It's all aboutdifferentially private clip test GD, amath trick that keeps data safe andmakes AI models better. Let's break itdown. First, imagine training a robot torecognize cats. You show it thousands ofimages, but one weird photo, a cat in ahat, could throw off the learning.Gradient clipping acts like a speedlimit, preventing wild updates. Buthere's the twist. It also boostsprivacy. By adding noise to training, wehide individual data like a shield.Traditional methods force the speedlimit clipping threshold to grow overtime, weakening privacy. This researchfixes that by using a fixed clippinglevel, keeping privacy strong whilesimplifying real world AI. Here's themagic. Under the right conditions, thismethod doesn't just stabilize learning,it accelerates it. By balancing noiseand clipping bias, models avoid crashesand zoom toward peak performance. Thisisn't theory. It works for everythingfrom image recognition to self-drivingcars. Privacy and speed. Now, that's thefuture of AI.

id: A Sneaky Trick Most FPS Games Use [70QDhd7YTUw]
video: ./part_11/dual_quaternions_sho/A Sneaky Trick Most FPS Games Use [70QDhd7YTUw].mp4
title: A Sneaky Trick Most FPS Games Use
subtitle: In many FPS games, the character thatyou control looks a bit like this. Ifyou move the character right up againstthe wall, though, you'll notice thatpart of the gun goes inside the wall.And so, what you should be seeing infirst person perspective is the front ofyour gun clipping into the wall. But invirtually all FPS games, the gun isfully visible at all times, no matterhow close you are to the wall. How isthis possible? One of the most commonways to get around gun clipping issimply by rendering the gun completelyseparately from the rest of the gameworld. It's basically like taking avideo and slapping a picture on top ofit so that it always shows up on top ofwhatever else is happening in the game.In this example, the gun is technicallyclipping into the wall, but it doesn'tlook like it because it exists in acompletely separate universe.[Music]

id: AR-15 Gas System [ml9tpzQ5BWs]
title: AR-15 Gas System
subtitle: AR-15 Gas SystemAs the expanding gases propel thebullet down the barrel,a portion escapes through the gas port.This high pressure gas quicklytravels through the gas tube,leading to a chamber between the bolt and the carrier.The dwell time is the time the bullet spendsbetween the gas port and the muzzle.The pressure from the gas trapped behind the bulletis necessary to cycle the rifle.The chamber between the bolt and carrieracts as a pneumatic cylinder.Since the bolt cannot move forward,the pressure forces the carrier to the rear.As the bullet clears the muzzle, the pressure dropsand at this point the carrier haspicked up enough inertia to retract the bolt.The two vents on the carrierpass over the gas rings on the boltreleasing the gases from the chamber.The bolt carrier continues to the rearas it extracts the empty shell case.

id: A Sneaky Trick Most FPS Games Use [70QDhd7YTUw]
video: ./part_11/default_logic_shorts/A Sneaky Trick Most FPS Games Use [70QDhd7YTUw].mp4
title: A Sneaky Trick Most FPS Games Use
subtitle: In many FPS games, the character thatyou control looks a bit like this. Ifyou move the character right up againstthe wall, though, you'll notice thatpart of the gun goes inside the wall.And so, what you should be seeing infirst person perspective is the front ofyour gun clipping into the wall. But invirtually all FPS games, the gun isfully visible at all times, no matterhow close you are to the wall. How isthis possible? One of the most commonways to get around gun clipping issimply by rendering the gun completelyseparately from the rest of the gameworld. It's basically like taking avideo and slapping a picture on top ofit so that it always shows up on top ofwhatever else is happening in the game.In this example, the gun is technicallyclipping into the wall, but it doesn'tlook like it because it exists in acompletely separate universe.[Music]
Image: ./part_11/default_logic_shorts/A Sneaky Trick Most FPS Games Use [70QDhd7YTUw].jpg
metadata: ./part_11/default_logic_shorts/A Sneaky Trick Most FPS Games Use [70QDhd7YTUw].info.json

id: The Entropy Paradox [X1dqsjKl318]
title: The Entropy Paradox
subtitle: Consider the ever intriguing entropyparadox which challenges ourunderstanding of order and chaos. Thisprinciple rooted in the second law ofthermodynamics suggests that theuniverse generally moves towards greaterdisorder or entropy. Yet paradoxically,life itself represents a curious riseagainst this gradient where livingorganisms create order from chaos. Thisfundamental contradiction leaves uspondering, how does life emerge andthrive in a universe seemingly destinedfordisorder? As scientists probe deeper,they uncover that local decreases inentropy might be sustained by largersystems increasing their disorder, acaptivating dance of balance andcontrast.Such exploration into entropy not onlyunravels the mysteries of our universebut also touches on the very nature ofexistence itself.

title: 🔥 What is Thermal Equilibrium? | Class 11 Physics & Chemistry | Thermodynamics Explained
subtitle: What is this thermal equilibrium in thermodynamics?Suppose I have twoobjects, object A and object B.Object A is very hot and object B isvery cold. When I kept these two objectsin contact with each other,after some time their temperature became equal.If you look at this process carefully,here the heat is being transferred from the hot objectto the cold object. As soon as thetemperature of these two objectsbecame equal, the flow of heat between them alsostopped. So these two objectsare in a state of thermal equilibrium with each other. Thermalequilibrium means that the temperature of both the objects is thesame, due to which noheat is able to flow between them. Simple.

subtitle: Let's understand entropy today with the help of a smalldaily life example.First of all, what is entropy? Entropyis disorderliness and degree of randomness. Somepeople are entropic. Suppose everything in your room isuniformed,everything is arranged in order. Yourbedsheets are absolutely uniform, your kurtas are neatly arranged,and your desk, studytable, all the books arearranged, pens are kept in the holder,everything is in order. What will happenwhen you use that room, everything willmove from its place and things will become non-uniform. Bedsheets will become non-uniform,kurtas will become non-uniform,things on your study table will also becomemessed up. Now, entropyis the creation of order in anything into disorder.This is called entropy. Entropymoves to disorderliness, disorderliness nevermoves to order. That is whyyou will have to use extra energy tobring things back into order. So,entropy is the degree ofrandomness.

id: The Enigmatic Nature of Entropy [hjVtxVMYo_s]
title: The Enigmatic Nature of Entropy
subtitle: Entropy is a fascinating concept thatmeasures disorder within a system,influencing everything fromthermodynamics to information theory. Inour universe, entropy tends to increase,which means that systems naturallyevolve from order to chaos. For example,imagine your bedroom after a weekwithout cleaning. It goes from neat tomessy, echoing the second law ofthermodynamics.Interestingly, entropy also plays acritical role in how we understand theflow of time, pointing to a futurefilled with potential randomness. So thenext time you witness the melting icecube or a tire going flat, rememberyou're observing the universe'sintricate dance with entropy.

subtitle: Bismillahirrahmanirrahim AssalamAlaikum Dear Student Student, aset which does not have any element iscalled an empty set. And a setwhich has a finite number of elements, i.e.,a limited number of elements, iscalled a finite set. And if the number ofelements is limited or infinity, thenit is called an infinity set.After that, such sets which do not have any element in common, arecalleddisjoint sets. After that, these are overlappingsets. If any two sets have even oneelement in common, i.e., at least onecommon element, then they are calledoverlapping sets. Such sets whose number ofelements is equal, i.e., if one has five, then theother has all five, are calledequivalent sets. And such sets having the same numberof elements are calledequal sets.

id: Statically & Dynamically Typed Languages [JdMIq3i00s4]
title: Statically & Dynamically Typed Languages
subtitle: In coding interviews, we may be asked whether thelanguage we are coding in isstatically typedor dynamically typed.To answer this, we need to understand both types.Statically typed languages ​​are those inwhich type checking happens at compile time itself.For example, Java, C, C++, Python, etc.These are all statically typed languages. Forexample, if we look at this Javasample code, we have defined an integernumber in it. After that, we are trying toadd a boolean value to our number,which is not allowedin Java. That is why we will get acompilation error here that we cannot use the plus operator toadd integer and boolean values. So,this is astatically typed language. On the other hand,we have dynamically typed languages ​​inwhich type checking happens at run time.For example, if we look at thisPython code, here we have defined a number,after that  We are trying to add a string inside the number,which is not allowed in Python, but herewe will not get any error while writing the code.Finally, when we execute the code,we will get an error thatwe cannot use the plus operator to add an int and a string.And you can look atthis chart which will help you remember whichlanguages ​​are statically typed andwhich are dynamic.

id: WHAT IS DYNAMIC PROGRAMMING？ [hJl6A_ckC9g]
title: WHAT IS DYNAMIC PROGRAMMING?
subtitle: What isDynamic ProgrammingDynamic Programming?Lets Understand with Example:How did you calculated so quick?Because you remembered there were FOUR, you simply added another 1 with 4so you don't waste your time to calculate again the whole answerDynamic Programming?It s a technique for solving a complex problem by first breaking into a collection of simpler subproblems, solving each subproblem just once, and then storing their solutions to avoid repetitive computations.Approcahes of Dynamic programmingThere are two approaches of dynamic programmingTop-down approach (Memoization)Bottom-up approach (Tabulation)Top-down approachMemorization is equal to the sum of recursion and caching. Recursion means calling the function itself, while caching means storing the intermediate resultsBottom-up approachIt solves the same kind of problems but it removes the recursion. If we remove the recursion, there is no stack overflow issue and no overhead of the recursive functions

title: Difference b/w Darwin's & Hugo deVries' Theory of Evolution #shorts #neet #biology
subtitle: Let's quickly differentiate betweenDurovansuri and Hugo Davies's theory ofevolution. According to Charles Darwin,evolution is a result ofsmall changes, which are called variations.These variations are slow,heritable, and directional.What does direction mean? If variations occurin the body of a living organism toadapt to changing environmental conditions,then these variations will bepassed on to the next generation, and then to the nextgeneration.Once variations occur in the body of an individual,they will definitely occur in the next generation. There isno turning back and asequential pattern is followed.Whereas, according to Ugadi Bridge, evolution is aresult of large changes, random changes,which are called mutations.
